	<article class="stat-text" id="post-660169199">
		<header>
			
				<p class="stat-notes"><a class="stat-bubble" href="http://christianromney.com/post/660169199/i-work-with-the-terminal-a-lot-in-fact-the-first#notes"><span class="stat-point"></span><em>0 notes</em></a></p>
				<time datetime="2010-06-03" pubdate><a rel="bookmark" href="http://christianromney.com/post/660169199/i-work-with-the-terminal-a-lot-in-fact-the-first">June 3, 2010</a></time>
			
			
		</header>
		<section>
			<p>I work with the terminal a lot. In fact, the first thing I do when I log in to my machine at work is to open up several shell tabs in Terminal and change directory. The specific directories I change to vary from project to project. With a little help from common shell commands and utilities, it&#8217;s easy to find out which directories you CD into most often. If you find yourself visiting a particular directory often, consider adding it to CDPATH.</p>

<p><script src="http://gist.github.com/423963.js?file=gistfile1.sh"></script></p>
			
		</section>
		<div class="stat-clear"></div>
		
				 
		
	</article>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
